<TITLE> Govt set to buy 21 locomotives for railway </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, June 30 (bdnews24.com)The government is set to procure 21 locomotives under loan agreements for Bangladesh Railway from South Korea and Japan, the communication minister said in the parliament on Tuesday. While replying to a query from Jamalpur-2 MP Faridul Haque Khan, Syed Abul Hossain said the 10 metre gauge diesel locomotives will be procured from South Korea within 2011, for which a loan agreement has already been signed. Another 11 locomotives will be bought from Japan by 2012 with assistance from JICA, he added. Jute policy On a query raised by Shatkhira-2 MP MA Jabbar, textiles and jute minister Abdul Latif Siddiqui said that the 'Jute Policy 2009' formulation process was on. The draft policy deals with issues related to jute goods production and exports for jute market expansion, increasing Bangladesh's share in the global jute market and developing the Jute Diversification and Promotion Centre into a fully fledged development concern. The policy also discusses and recommends diversification of jute goods and providing banking services to the industrial entrepreneurs and affording debtors opportunities for repayment of accumulated debts on easy terms. Reopening shutdown factories Siddiqui, replying to a question by Sylhet-3 MP Mahmud-Us-Samad Chowdhury, said the BNP-led alliance government had closed down Adamjee Jute Mills Ltd, Nishat Jute Mills Ltd and Doulatpur Jute Mills Ltd. The incumbent government has decided to reopen them under arrangement with Bangladesh Jute Mills Corporation. A committee has already initiated activities to re-commission Doulatpur Jute Mills Ltd in Khulna, he said. bdnew
